<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF110-343-300  </DOCNO><DOCID>10 343 300.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DBMS  Dec 1990 v3 n13 p44(12).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Transaction processing: how SQL handles transactions in largemultiuser applications. (structured query language) (Includesrelated article on microcomputer database management systemtransaction processing support)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Groff, James R.; Weinberg, Paul N.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Database updates are instigated by real-world transactions.andO;Transactions are a sequence of one or more structured query logic(SQL) states forming a logical unit.andP;  The SQL statements thatcomprise a transaction are usually closely related and performinterdependent actions.andP;  Each statement is responsible forperforming some portion of a task.andP;  All are necessary to completethe task.andP;  Database transactions are supported by SQL through twoSQL transaction processing statements: Commit and Rollback.andO;Commit signifies the successful end of a transaction, notifyingthe database management system (DBMS) that all statements havem been executed.andP;  Rollback signals the unsuccessful end of atransaction, telling the DBMS that the user does not want tocomplete the transaction.andP;  Transactions are important torecovering a database following system failure.andP;  Only transactionscommitted at time of failure remain.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Structured Query LanguageOn-Line Transaction ProcessingMultiuser SoftwareData Base Management SystemsStatements.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Structure of the sample database. (chart)SQL transaction concept. (chart)Commit and rollback. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>